<div id="review_620107649" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/620107649" />
    <a title="Susan A." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15959475-susan-a"><img alt="Susan A." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1422896769p2/15959475.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/620107649?book_show_action=true">May 20, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Susan A." class="user" itemprop="url" name="Susan A." href="/user/show/15959475-susan-a">Susan A.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780440195344" href="/book/show/679703.The_Windflower">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer620107649" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9070109508121291048">I was lucky enough that in HS a friend&apos;s grandmother (or aunt) worked in a bookstore. When books were being discontinued it was accepted practice to rip off the front cover and throw the book away. (SACRILEGE!!!) She would instead, bring them to us ... those of us who had read the school library, perhaps like me who had read every book in the library of the small town where I spent my summers ...<br/><br/>This book spoke to me right off ... I read this book until the binding cracked and fell apart and I&apos;d</span>
  <span id="freeText9070109508121291048" style="display:none">I was lucky enough that in HS a friend's grandmother (or aunt) worked in a bookstore. When books were being discontinued it was accepted practice to rip off the front cover and throw the book away. (SACRILEGE!!!) She would instead, bring them to us ... those of us who had read the school library, perhaps like me who had read every book in the library of the small town where I spent my summers ...<br /><br />This book spoke to me right off ... I read this book until the binding cracked and fell apart and I'd put it back together with binding tape and carefully placed glue in several different places. I made my own cover for this book. I read it until I could quote character and what they said by page, if you gave me a page number. <br /><br />This book is witty and fresh ... Merry and Devon are heart stoppingly adorable. Cat is OMG brooding and sexy ... and that hair ~swoon~<br /><br />Raven is every girl's daydream of a best friend, puppy and sweet younger brother all rolled into one. <br /><br />Morgan ... well, Rand Morgan was to my teenage self what Ryodan is to my adult self (if I'd met Ryo as a teenage girl I'm not sure I would have survived the experience). He scares you within an inch of your life and keeps you perched there ... yet at the same time, somewhere deep in your soul you know you are safe with him and he'll bust the gates of hell to protect or rescue you.<br /><br />If you can get your hands on this READ IT!!! In fact ... well I'm off to search now ;)<br /><br />P.S. After reading this again, I am more convinced than ever that Cat needs his own book, and its a crying shame this wasn't done.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9070109508121291048" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


